inant views on this issue have been strongly shaped by ideas of both race and place. But just as important, who is permitted to ask, and answer this question?This collection examines the changing roles of race and place in the politics of defining Indigenous identities in the Americas. Drawing on case studies of Indigenous communities across North America, the Caribbean, Central America, and South America, it is a rare volume to compare Indigenous experience throughout the western hemisphere. The contributors question the vocabulary, legal mechanisms, and applications of science in constructing the identities of Indigenous populations, and consider ideas of nation, land, and tradition in moving indigeneity beyond race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectsxAmerica. 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectszAmerica. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEthnic identityxAmerica. 0aIndigenous peopleszAmericaxEthnic identity. 0aPolitics and culturexAmerica. 0aPolitics and culturezAmerica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aForte, Maxmillian C. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266799040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667990423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667990.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK